        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat: channel echo / session pinning",
        "body": "## Pin-from-here: channel-agnostic turn mirroring\n\nA session can mirror its turns to other threads bound to the **same** session. You\nrun `/pin on` in a thread; from then on, when any other thread of that session\ndrives a turn, this thread receives it — rendered **natively through its own\nchannel's dispatch**, persisted as that channel's own turn.\n\n### Authorization (the rework)\n\nThe original revision let an operator add an echo target to an arbitrary chat id;\nthe maintainer flagged that as streaming session content to any chat. This revision\nremoves that surface entirely:\n\n- **`/pin`** is in-chat, opt-in, and binds only the session already bound to *this*\n  thread — every mirror recipient is, by construction, an already-authorized\n  participant of that session. There is no \"stream to an arbitrary chat id\" path.\n- Operator echo adds require a session participant (`targetMatchesSessionParticipant`),\n  fail-closed.\n\n### How the mirror renders — channel-agnostic, by reuse not reimplementation\n\nThe agent runs **once**; its parsed event stream is broadcast on the agent-event\nbus keyed by `runId`. For each pinned target, the core hands that target's **own\nchannel dispatch** a bus-sourced `replyResolver` (`createMirrorReplyResolver`) that\nreplays the origin run's stream instead of calling the model:\n\n- `dispatchInboundMessageWithDispatcher` already accepts a pluggable `replyResolver`.\n  `launchMirrorDispatch` (core, channel-agnostic) drives each target through its\n  registered mirror dispatcher with that resolver.\n- Telegram registers a thin `dispatchMirror` that synthesizes an inbound for the\n  pinned chat/thread and runs its **existing** `dispatchTelegramMessage` with the\n  resolver. So drafts, streaming, formatting, and persistence all follow **that\n  account's own config** — streaming-capable + on → the mirror streams; off → final\n  only. Nothing is forced; nothing is reimplemented per channel.\n- **Loop-safe by construction:** the `replyResolver` bypasses the agent-run path, so\n  a mirror turn never re-enters the mirror fan-out. The post-hoc final echo skips any\n  target a mirror turn rendered (handled-mark dedup) so there's no double delivery.\n\nThis replaces the earlier per-channel streaming-echo *renderer* (telegram-only,\nreimplemented rendering) with one small channel-agnostic mechanism that reuses each\nchannel's pipeline. **Net −894 LOC**: deletes `echo-renderer*`, `echo-streaming`,\n`streaming-progress-callbacks`, the `registerEchoRendererFactory` plugin-api\nplumbing, and the `plugin-sdk/channel-echo` subpath; adds a small core\nlauncher/registry (reusing the existing `echo-mirror-resolver`) plus a thin telegram\nadapter.\n\n### Real behavior proof (Telegram-desktop, mantis-equivalent)\n\nRecreation of the Mantis telegram-desktop flow on a local patched crabbox: a real\ngateway built from this branch (current `openclaw/openclaw` main + this work),\nTelegram Desktop + the user-driver + screen capture, driven by a **real\n`claude-cli/claude-sonnet-4-6` backend with an exec tool call** (not a mock).\n\nA Telegram thread runs `/pin on`; webchat then drives the same session with a\ntool-using prompt (`sleep 3; hostname` — output not derivable from context). The\npinned thread renders the **webchat-origin turn's reply natively** — including the\nreal tool result — through telegram's own dispatch:\n\n1. `/verbose on` → \"⚙️ Verbose logging enabled.\"\n2. `/pin on` → **\"📌 Pinned. This thread will mirror turns from other threads of this session.\"**\n3. `📱 [via webchat] Use your exec (bash) tool to run … sleep 3; hostname …`\n4. The pinned thread receives the real reply: **\"The hostname is `crabbox-golden-crayfish-fa445ed1`.\"** — the actual box hostname, i.e. a real `hostname` exec run by the webchat-triggered turn, rendered natively in the pinned Telegram thread via the channel-agnostic mirror dispatch.\n\n<img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/anagnorisis2peripeteia/openclaw/proof/pin-from-here-evidence/.proof/pin-from-here-mirror-dispatch.png\" width=\"50%\" alt=\"the webchat-origin turn's reply rendered natively in the pinned Telegram thread via mirror-dispatch\">\n\nMechanism confirmed in the gateway log for the filmed run: `launchMirrorDispatch`\nfires for the webchat-origin turn (origin = webchat, telegram target not\nself-excluded, dispatcher found); the telegram `dispatchMirror` builds the synthetic\ninbound (`context=BUILT`) and runs `dispatchTelegramMessage` for the full turn\n(`message processed: channel=telegram messageId=0 … completed`); exactly one reply\nlands (post-hoc assistant echo skipped by the handled-mark, no duplicate).\n\n#### Riding the destination's verbose config\n\nBecause the mirror re-runs each target's own dispatch, it inherits *that*\naccount's streaming/verbose config rather than forcing anything. With the daily\ndriver's setup (`verboseDefault: on`, `streaming.mode: progress`, reasoning +\n`toolProgressDetail: raw`), a webchat-triggered turn renders the **full\ninterleaved durable record** in the pinned thread — assistant commentary (`💬`)\nand tool summaries (`🛠️`) as standalone messages, exactly as a native turn there\nwould (matching #91976):\n\n<img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/anagnorisis2peripeteia/openclaw/proof/pin-from-here-evidence/.proof/pin-from-here-verbose-mirror.png\" width=\"50%\" alt=\"webchat-origin turn rendering interleaved commentary and tool summaries natively in the pinned Telegram thread\">\n\nThis exercised a real gap: the CLI runner emits `stream:\"tool\"` events with both\n`phase:\"start\"` and `phase:\"result\"`, and the resolver was routing every tool\nevent to `onToolStart` — so the durable `🛠️` summaries (driven by `onToolResult`)\nwere dropped from the mirror while `💬` commentary still rendered. Fixed by running\nthe bus tool events through the same `createCliToolSummaryTracker` the native CLI\ndispatch uses, so the mirror's tool summaries are byte-identical, in both streaming\nmodes; the target dispatch still gates the actual send on verbose.\n\n### Tests + CI\n\n- `tsgo:core`: clean. Full `oxlint` shard gate (`run-oxlint-shards`): clean across\n  the PR surface (type-aware rules included).\n- The PR-relevant vitest matrix is green (`infra`, `auto-reply-*`, `gateway-core`/\n  `methods`, `commands`, `extension-telegram`, `hooks`, `plugin-sdk`): the\n  bus-sourced resolver (incl. the tool-summary replay), handled-mark dedup, and\n  `/pin` fan-out are covered. The `gateway-server` shard's auth/device-identity\n  failures are pre-existing and environmental — identical `15 failed | 92 passed`\n  on pristine `main` (merge-base `9827490`) in the same container.\n\n### AI assistance\n\nBuilt with AI assistance (Claude). The channel-agnostic design, implementation,\ntests, and the local telegram-desktop proof were produced with AI; the architecture\ndirection (mirror through each channel's own dispatch, ride its config) and review\nare the author's.\n\n",
